ize:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe the development of low-carbon gases and modern gas appliances can significantly decarbonise the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s use of heat and i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ncrease energy security. However, policy has steered much more towards the potential for electric heating technologies and district heating. While these are areas to develop and investigate, both cost and consumer issues mean that electric heating and dist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rict heating will not be able to replace gas heating any time soon.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that a more joined-up approach between Government departments and regulators is required to deliver ‘green’ sources of gas such as biomethane and hydrogen. There is also a need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to offer support for the development of low-carbon gas appliances such as gas absorption heat pumps.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Thank you for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opportunity to respond to this i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nquiry into ‘heat’. As a key part of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s energy market and a leading innovator in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e sector of low-carbon heat, we hope you find our comments useful. If you require any further information please don’t hesitate to get in touch.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a gas transporter and engineering company, we will be focussing on the following questions from the terms o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f reference:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">UK</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What are the lock-in, costs and </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">GHG savings from the promotion of different forms of domestic heating solution?</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Thermal storage is a potentia</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">l</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">l</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">y</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annual</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ly.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About Us</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scotia Gas Networks is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s second largest gas distribution company operating Southern Gas Networks which operates across the South and South-East of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and Scotland Gas Networks which operates across the whole of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We distribute gas to 5.8 million customers and our a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">im is to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lead the way in energy delivery, engineering and sustainability. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> leader in the development of sustainable and low-carbon gas grids and are the market leader in biomethane injection operating the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s first test biomethane injection</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> project at Didcot in Oxfordshire and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s first commercial project at Rainbarrow farm with our partners JV Energen near Poundbury, Dorset. We are also involved in a number of hydrogen projects investigating the potential to inject hydrogen into the ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tworks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Role of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’s Gas Network</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has one of the most developed gas grids in the world in terms of geographical coverage, technical excellence and safety. 84% of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s homes are connected to the gas network and people who are not on the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> gas network often aspire to be connected to the network. In fact, extending the gas network to serve more homes and businesses is one of the major requests from our stakeholders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In terms of the consumption of heat, gas dominates with over 70% of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s total heat consumption coming from gas. 57% of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s total heat use is in the domestic sector with the remainder occurring in commercial and industry</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In total, there are around 43 million domestic gas appliances in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reason for this domi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nance is primarily associated with the economics of using gas for heat; gas currently offers the lowest levelised cost of heat for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consumers. This results from the fact that the costs in the network have already been sunk, we have a well developed gas i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndustry and the actual price of gas is relatively low compared to other forms of energy. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This relative low cost is likely to stay for the foreseeable future with Government’s own predictions for future gas prices now being lowered due to the emergence of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> new sources of unconventional gas. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Studies have suggested that low-carbon heating technologies such as heat pumps and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">district heating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are likely to be more expensive than standard gas systems and require financial support right up to 2050 and beyond</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As well as being cost effective, the use of gas for heating is also very responsive as the network is designed to match both diurnal and seasonal demand changes. The instantaneous capacity of the gas network is around four times larger than the electricity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> network and without gas, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> energy system would be very different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">requiring a much larger power generation capacity and a greatly strengthened electricity transmission and distribution network. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This responsiveness means that gas consumers are quickl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y able to heat their homes and also produce instantaneous hot water. Along with the relative low cost of gas, this is the reason why consumers appear generally happy with gas heating systems</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What are the relative merits of using gas to directly </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As mentioned previously, the costs of gas for heating are nearly always lower than the costs of using other energy sources such as air source or ground source</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> heat pumps. It is worth recognising that heat pump systems will have both hig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">her capital costs at the time of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> installation and also higher ongoing operating costs due to the higher price of electricity compared to gas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Electric heat pumps can use less </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">units of energy than gas boiler heating systems however, electricity retail prices are around three times higher than gas prices and this divergence is expected to increase as gas prices remain relatively flat and electricity prices increase</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This means t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat the current low system efficiency of heat pumps installed in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as measured by the Energy Saving Trust</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would have to increase significantly to match current annual gas fuel costs and then increase even more in the future as electricity becomes mor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e expensive. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With regards to carbon emission reductions, although heat pumps are seen to be a low-carbon heating system in the future, under today’s grid mix, unless the heat pumps can perform with very high system efficiencies (much higher than we have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">seen so far), heat pumps could actually increase emissions compared to a gas boiler system. This is because a modern gas boiler burns gas very efficiently at around 90%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. However, if the power for a heat pump is coming from the grid, this electri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">city is likely to be generated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> partly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by a coal or gas power station and will have a high carbon intensity. Under this scenario, there are significant losses at the power station and also on the electricity network.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Exacerbating this issue is the fact tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t heating systems such as heat pumps will often be running at full output at times of peak demand and this can be difficult to shift. This means that the heat pump systems are running at the time when the carbon intensity of the electricity grid is at its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highest. These marginal emission factors are often not taken into account in models. As mentioned previously, increasing volumes of heat pumps will require a higher electricity peak capacity as well as increases in capacity to the network. These investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s would be associated with increased costs for consumers particularly as this plant would most likely be low load-factor peaking plant.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although it is widely expected that over the coming years the electricity grid will be decarbonised, by when and to wha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t degree is very uncertain and even the Government’s own gas generation strategy included a pathway which showed that in 2030, 45% of the UK’s power generation could be coming f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rom closed cycle gas turbines and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> average grid carbon intensity would be 200g/k</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wh. Combining this with the marginal emissions issue mentioned in the previous paragraph, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it appears to us that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it would currently make very little sense to switch on gas households to electric heat pumps.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Looking at this issue of heat pumps more widely, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it is important to recognise the difficulties associated with switching consumers away from gas to heat pump systems. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this would be achieved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, when costs may be higher and system comfort may be lower, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has not yet been resolved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Although the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Government’s 2013 heat strategy update</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recognised that their previous strategy included potentially too many heat pumps, the update</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> version still expects that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gas consumers will switch t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o heat pump</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> systems. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that further research is neede</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d to assess whether heat pump systems are able to meet customer needs and requirements to the same extent as gas. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that it makes sense where possible to try and decarbonise the gas grid as this is an option which allows you to decarbonise heati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng but also allows customers to continue to use gas, which they are generally satisfied with in terms of relative price, convenience and comfort</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. There are a numbe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r of sources of low-carbon gas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which can be used including biomethane and hyd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rogen. We expla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in more about this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in paragraphs 32 and 33.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The main explanation for the low penetration of community heating schemes to date is the relatively high cost of providing heat through a heat network in comparison to gas heating. There are also major issues associated with the physical development of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se networks. The main driver of the higher cost is the network of hot water pipes needed to distribute the heat to individual dwellings. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Historically, community heating schemes in the UK have had a very bad reputation.  Many urban areas contained a schem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e in the 1950s/60s but many of these have now been removed due to their poor design, construction and economic performance. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As with heat pumps, it is important to recognise the difficulties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> associated with switching customers onto district heat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing systems. Recent research into consumer attitudes to heat technologies has shown that there would be significant ‘barrier costs’ associated with persuading homeowners in existing properties to join a heat network</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although the Government’s heat strat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">egy update recognises that their previous strategy overestimated the role for heat networks in 2050, the updated version still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anticipate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s that a large number of consumers will switch from gas to heat network systems. To achieve widespread expansion of hea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t networks will require major regulatory intervention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well as significant consumer engagement.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What are the lock-in, costs and GHG savings from the promotion of different forms of domestic heating solutions?</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Decisions made today could affect the e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nergy system for many years to come however, in terms of appliances, this system inertia is reducing as modern appliances tend to have shorter lives. The gas network is one area where we are already locked in although there is little we can do to avoid thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is imperative that as a gas transporter we focus on safety and so we must maintain our network so that it can deliver gas safely on the coldest winter days. We therefore invest, with approval from our regulator, in repair and replacement work. Alth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ough in our new regulatory package, the focus has moved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> slightly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from replace</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to repair, we are still replacing significant number of pipes with on average around 900km of mains replacement each year up to 2021. New polyethylene gas mains can have a life of over 50 years and so these are very much long term investments.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We do not h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owever believe that this will necessarily lock the UK into a high carbon scenario.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As we have already mentioned in paragraph 14, currently, heat pumps are likely to emit more CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> emissions than an equivalent gas boiler and so switching people from gas to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">heat pump systems doesn’t seem sensible at this point in time. As the electricity grid decarbonises, heat pumps systems are expected to become lower carbon however, there are questions over how long this will take. At this point it doesn’t appear that inst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">alling a heat pump today would save any carbon over its lifetime. A heat pump would however cost more to install and run than a gas system.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Homes and buildings currently with gas heating can have their carbon emissions significantly reduced as there are s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">till many areas where emissions can be saved through energy efficiency measures. This includes the roll-out of insulation but also through the replacement of older non-condensing boilers. Modern boilers can operate at over 90% efficiency saving money for h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ouseholders and also reducing carbon emissions. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Boiler replacement is one of the Committee on Climate Change’s key residential indicators and they suggest that over the next decade this could save 6 million tonnes of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> According to the Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK was well ahead of the boiler replacement indicator last year</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and this momentum has continued into this year with the assistance for boiler replacement from the ‘green deal cashback scheme’</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is also still a long way to go regarding heating controls with a significant number of customers having either no heating controls or insufficient controls. The installation of controls is very often a cost effective measure to save money for consume</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rs and also reduce carbon emissions. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also believe that much more can be done to reduce the carbon intensity of the gas network. As we mentioned in section 18, we have been a partner in the UK’s leading low-carbon gas injection projects. We fundamental</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly believe that through innovation and research and development, the UK’s gas network can play a leading role in the decarbonisation of heat supplies. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The current focus of policy support in this area is the renewable heat incentive which rewards biometha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ne injection. We hope to have 100 biomethane plants connected to our system by 2020. However, some regulatory barriers to these projects remain and are holding back the development of this industry. A much more joined up approach between the different agen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cies involved with biomethane would help support the industry to overcome the remaining regulatory hurdles.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are also next generation low-carbon gases such as syngas, hydrogen and next generation biofuels which could potentially produce very large qu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">antities of gas for network injection. Focussed research and development in this area is necessary in order to drive this forward.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The domestic RHI is clearly a much better proposition for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">households not on the gas grid as the counterfactual used to work out the tariffs is based on off-grid properties. This means that the potential financial return from the RHI for homeowners currently using gas is less than for those off the gas grid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">domestic RHI is available for homes on the gas network and although, as mentioned previously, it may be less rewarding than for homes off the gas grid there may be some scope for development. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One particular technology type which we are interested in and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">believe should be promoted is hybrid heat pumps. These systems combine a small air source heat pump with a gas boiler to combine efficiency with responsiveness. DECC’s recently updated heat strategy suggests that these systems could be important up to and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">beyond 2050 as they can provide low-carbon heat but also manage spikes in electricity demand. It is expected that from next year the domestic RHI will support the heat pump part of these systems however this is unlikely to drive the level of support requir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed to meet the Government’s targets</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One technology type which could be useful for households but will not be supported under current RHI proposals is gas absorption heat pumps. These systems are not yet commercially available at the domestic scale but a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re used at larger scales. Again, DECC’s heat strategy recognised these systems as potentially important as they can produce significant increases in efficiency and carbon reductions cost effectively. Because of the potential importance of these systems, we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> believe that they should be supported by the RHI as there are currently no other drivers to develop this technology.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Thermal storage is a potential</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ly</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annually.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As we mentioned in section 13, the instantaneous peak demand on the gas networ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">k is significantly higher than the demand on the electricity network as the network is designed to match both diurnal and seasonal demand changes. There is a huge amount of energy stored in the gas network and we believe that a key form of heat storage in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the future will be hydrogen.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hydrogen has the potential to store excess renewable electricity at times of high output and low demand and this hydrogen could potentially be injected into the gas network for later usage. Currently there are no commercial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">drivers for this technology however, we believe that DECC should have a clear vision and strategy for hydrogen in order to drive the industry forward.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px